downloadable, free, streamable
client for their World of

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:41.929
Warcraft MMO.

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:43.340
Effectively, if I recall
correctly,

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:44.650
it was like 25 megs.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:46.530
You would download it, you
could actually play up to

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:48.820
level 20 for free
with this thing.

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:51.000
And what you'd do is you would
download it, and all it

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.500
basically gave you was your
character creation screen,

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:54.990
knowing that a user's
going to sit there

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:55.450
and tweak with stuff.

00:08:55.450 --> 00:08:57.230
And while they're playing, it
would be streaming in data in

00:08:57.230 --> 00:08:57.630
the background.

00:08:57.630 --> 00:08:58.665
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Exactly.

00:08:58.665 --> 00:09:00.570
WOLFF DOBSON: I mean really, if
you think about it, this is

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:05.770
the problem that we've been
going at for 15 years.

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:08.350
And the PlayStation 2 was all
about well, we have all these

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:10.360
different streaming paths
that are going through.

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:12.160
And we have to make sure that
we're actually streaming the

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.390
textures in live as we're
rendering it.

00:09:14.390 --> 00:09:18.180
And you always had to build in
the lag from oh, we've got to

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:19.820
get it off disk, then we get
it into memory, from memory

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:21.425
onto the graphics runner.

00:09:21.425 --> 00:09:23.620
We've been doing this
for 20 years now.

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:24.920
COLT MCANLIS: Yeah, it's
definitely an old problem and,

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:26.530
in fact, solved very well.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:28.110
I don't know if you guys
remember playing Jak and

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:30.680
Daxter back on the PS2, this
had probably one of the

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:32.440
greatest solutions I've
ever seen for this.

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:34.540
So it was a live streaming
world, probably one of the

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:36.900
most successful and one of the
first to really do it.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.250
I don't know if you guys ever
noticed, but if you like just

00:09:39.250 --> 00:09:42.920
took off in one direction as
fast as you could go, and the

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:45.990
data wasn't streamed in yet, the
designers actually put in

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:46.390
something funny.

00:09:46.390 --> 00:09:48.510
They'd trip your character.

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:51.220
Your character would fall over
and play like a 30-second get

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:52.925
up animation allowing
enough time for

00:09:52.925 --> 00:09:53.795
the data to be streamed.

00:09:53.795 --> 00:09:54.310
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: That's great.

00:09:54.310 --> 00:09:55.245
COLT MCANLIS: That's
brilliant.

00:09:55.245 --> 00:09:56.885
WOLFF DOBSON: It's like
those doors in Mass

00:09:56.885 --> 00:09:58.885
Effect, or the elevators.

00:09:58.885 --> 00:09:59.665
TODD KERPELMAN: The elevators.

00:09:59.665 --> 00:10:01.090
WOLFF DOBSON: Ah,
the elevators.

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:02.210
Man, this elevator's
taking forever.

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:04.010
Why did we ever install this?

00:10:04.010 --> 00:10:06.100
COLT MCANLIS: Why is floor
two nine million

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:07.220
feet above floor one?

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:08.990
WOLFF DOBSON: Why didn't
we install a pole

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:09.900
just to slide down?

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:10.935
I don't understand.

00:10:10.935 --> 00:10:12.840
No, but it is an old problem.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:14.150
And it's a problem--

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:16.510
well, and I can go all the way
back to-- when I was working

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:19.600
on basketball for the Dreamcast
where you would put

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:20.400
the ball up.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:22.730
And we didn't have the physics
running all the way forward to

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:24.250
know whether or not the ball
is going to go in.

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:27.610
So we had to stream four or five
different audio clips.

00:10:27.610 --> 00:10:29.830
It was like it's in, it's
off the rim, no

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:32.600
good, all these things.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:35.810
And then by the time the ball
was coming down the arch, we

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:38.660
knew we had five of them
in memory, and then

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:39.370
it wouldn't go in.

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:40.750
And then we'd go ah, it
was this one, and

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:41.850
then we'd play that.

00:10:41.850 --> 00:10:44.360
And every now and then we were
spectacularly wrong.

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:46.730
So we'd jump up and swat it
away, and then the commentary

00:10:46.730 --> 00:10:49.810
just wouldn't say anything
because we had nothing ready.

00:10:49.810 --> 00:10:52.190
COLT MCANLIS: So let
me ask you this.

00:10:52.190 --> 00:10:54.800
Do you feel that in the modern
age of development we have

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:58.500
right now that users still
benefit from streaming of

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:01.610
assets and being closer to
instant load as possible?

00:11:01.610 --> 00:11:03.730
Do you think that's something
that users actually care

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:07.155
about, that will actually drive
sales for developers?

00:11:07.155 --> 00:11:08.800
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yes.

00:11:08.800 --> 00:11:09.720
Yeah, I do.

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:10.420
TODD KERPELMAN: I
mean, I think it

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:11.870
depends on the system.

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:18.340
Like if I'm going through a
traditional model where I go

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:21.450
on to Steam and I say hey, I'm
going to buy this thing.

00:11:21.450 --> 00:11:24.590
Actually, at that point I've
bought it and I've sort of

00:11:24.590 --> 00:11:27.160
accepted that maybe, depending
on my internet connection, it

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:30.480
might take a few hours until
I can actually play.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:34.050
If I could play it right away,
or if I could start playing

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:35.850
and then it asked me for
my credit card or

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:36.710
something like that.

00:11:36.710 --> 00:11:37.950
You know, I bet you--

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:39.330
I'm going to say I bet
you could get a few

00:11:39.330 --> 00:11:41.348
more sales that way.

00:11:41.348 --> 00:11:43.630
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Let me give a
scenario, and I think that we

00:11:43.630 --> 00:11:45.280
could all relate to this.

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:47.050
You get home from work
and you've got 30

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:48.880
minutes to play a game.

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:51.370
You don't want to spend 10 to
15 minutes of those waiting

00:11:51.370 --> 00:11:54.100
for everything to load up, and
get everything started.

00:11:54.100 --> 00:11:56.620
You just want to drop in, play
your 30 minutes, and get out.

00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:59.450
So streaming absolutely
will help there.

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:02.370
And it's going to make our
very busy schedules

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:03.730
have room for games.

00:12:03.730 --> 00:12:06.720
And really high quality games,
too, not just small games.

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:07.520
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I think

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:09.820
streaming and caching together.

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:13.385
Once you have it downloaded,
then you are able to drop back

00:12:13.385 --> 00:12:15.530
in instantaneously.

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:17.870
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: I think if you
organize your game world in

00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:21.180
such a way that the immediate
assets you need are five to 10

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:23.870
megs, and then you're streaming
in after that, I

00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:25.775
think you could still do
it without caching.

00:12:25.775 --> 00:12:27.270
TODD KERPELMAN: I don't know.

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:28.990
I guess that's assuming
everyone's got a very good

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:29.780
internet connection.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:30.860
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: Yes, yeah.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:32.810
TODD KERPELMAN: I would love
it if it started streaming

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:33.520
while I was playing.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:35.730
And then when I was done
playing, it just kept

00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:36.360
downloading all the game data.

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:37.290
WOLFF DOBSON: Just kept
chewing on it.

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:40.370
Well, I think Steam
does that, right?

00:12:40.370 --> 00:12:44.360
You can start playing Episode
2 when it's half downloaded,

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:45.480
and then it'll keep--

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:47.390
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: They have
some checkpoints where

00:12:47.390 --> 00:12:48.350
you can start it.

00:12:48.350 --> 00:12:50.780
COLT MCANLIS: Well, I think Todd
actually brought up the

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:52.660
crux of the situation here.

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:53.990
We're definitely at an
inflection point.

00:12:53.990 --> 00:12:56.500
I think if you're a game
developer right now and you

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:59.240
haven't read the millions of
articles that are talking

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:01.390
about the monetization
differences in the mobile

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:04.130
space, then you're living
under a rock.

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:06.890
Right now we're seeing lots of
studies showing freemium is

00:13:06.890 --> 00:13:09.340
definitely dominating in terms
of monetization over

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:10.460
premium-style content.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:12.000
Like there's still the niche for
it, they're still there,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.730
especially in the Steam platform
where AAA hardcore

00:13:15.730 --> 00:13:17.980
developers work in that
premium model.

00:13:17.980 --> 00:13:20.580
But I think Todd really caught
on to it where you said you

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:23.160
started with if this is a
premium content, I expect to

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:24.240
buy it and take some time.

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:25.820
But if this is a freemium-style
content--

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.530
WOLFF DOBSON: I just want
it to be there.

00:13:27.530 --> 00:13:27.930
COLT MCANLIS: Right.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:30.840
And so that's where I think
the crux is right there.

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:34.870
Even with the monetization
methods that we're seeing have

00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:37.200
huge success in the industry
right now, the freemium-style

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:40.330
content, we're still sort of
gated by this mental model

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:43.090
that consumers have given
from our silos.

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:45.140
That I'm going to click a button
and then it's going to

00:13:45.140 --> 00:13:47.730
take some time to download, and
then I can play it later.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:50.110
And that's where, again, I think
I come back to wanting

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:52.680
the webification of games.

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:55.060
Wanting the ability to send
someone a link and have them

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:57.290
instant load it without having
all this install and

00:13:57.290 --> 00:13:58.540
everything.

00:13:58.540 --> 00:13:59.390
That's really a dream of mine.

00:13:59.390 --> 00:14:01.490
That's something that John and I
hopefully will work on a lot

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:02.380
more in the coming years.

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:04.540
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I mean,
I also just like applying

00:14:04.540 --> 00:14:05.360
patches, too.

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:06.860
COLT MCANLIS: Oh, yeah.

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:09.890
WOLFF DOBSON: Anybody who's
ever left their favorite

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:12.390
console or whatever, or their
game, alone for a while,

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:14.855
they're like yeah, I haven't
played this in forever-- aw.

00:14:14.855 --> 00:14:15.890
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: And there
goes your 30 minutes.

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:17.610
WOLFF DOBSON: Yeah, exactly.

00:14:17.610 --> 00:14:20.400
So definitely all that stuff.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:22.640
I do find it interesting though,
especially for mobile

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:27.290
gaming, I kind of do want it
all on the device before I

00:14:27.290 --> 00:14:28.280
walk out the door.

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:29.600
Because I don't actually
know what my

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:30.600
connectivity is going to be.

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:31.210
COLT MCANLIS: That's
fair, yeah.

00:14:31.210 --> 00:14:31.940
Absolutely.

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:33.770
WOLFF DOBSON: Especially for--

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:35.440
I'm going to Alaska
pretty soon.

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:38.220
So no idea what my internet
connection is going to be.

00:14:38.220 --> 00:14:38.734
TODD KERPELMAN: I don't know
what your coverage

00:14:38.734 --> 00:14:39.630
is going to be there.

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:42.900
WOLFF DOBSON: I'm going to be
adjusting the moose antler.

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:44.150
Yeah, OK.

00:14:46.372 --> 00:14:48.210
COLT MCANLIS: Moose internet
connection.

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:48.910
Where do you plug-in?

00:14:48.910 --> 00:14:50.280
Just get a moose.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:52.030
WOLFF DOBSON: I'm very,
very sorry to all

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:55.311
of our Alaska watchers.

00:14:55.311 --> 00:14:56.470
TODD KERPELMAN: If they're
watching then

00:14:56.470 --> 00:14:58.400
they have good internet.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:01.020
WOLFF DOBSON: Well, I actually
am going out to the national

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:02.860
parks and stuff where the
coverage is going to be poor.

00:15:02.860 --> 00:15:05.185
And I'm bringing my
Nexus 7 with me.

00:15:05.185 --> 00:15:07.010
COLT MCANLIS: Well, I think
that's just the next place we

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:10.210
should put out Google Fiber is
the Alaskan wildlife park.

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:12.580
WOLFF DOBSON: Is Denali.

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:14.680
Three fourths of the way up
Denali there's like a bunch of

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:16.796
code books.

00:15:16.796 --> 00:15:17.880
COLT MCANLIS: I think
it works.

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:20.110
JOHN MCCUTCHAN: We'll send
Pitbull up there.

00:15:20.110 --> 00:15:20.310
There you go.

00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:21.350
WOLFF DOBSON: Because
he's already in

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:24.258
Kodiak, it would be awesome.

00:15:24.258 --> 00:15:25.650
COLT MCANLIS: It's all right,
we're completely off-base.

00:15:25.650 --> 00:15:26.880
TODD KERPELMAN: No, that's
not, that's fine.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.100
WOLFF DOBSON: So next
question, Todd.

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:30.790
TODD KERPELMAN: Well, I was
actually going to touch on the

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:34.230
freemium model.

00:15:34.230 --> 00:15:36.685
Do you feel like that's the
future for all games?

00:15:36.685 --> 00:15:39.260
COLT MCANLIS: Oh, absolutely
not, no, no, no.

00:15:39.260 --> 00:15:42.660
The way I correlate freemium
versus premium is much like

00:15:42.660 --> 00:15:44.910
television versus movies
right now.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:48.190
Like there is always a market
that someone wants that rich,

00:15:48.190 --> 00:15:51.070
immersive, interactive
environment, and that is never

00:15:51.070 --> 00:15:51.660
going to go away.

00:15:51.660 --> 00:15:55.710
I think the fact that Steam
sales and consoles actually

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:59.360
stayed relatively strong
considering how much attention

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:02.660
and money is now in the mobile
market is proof that there is

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:04.710
definitely a market there and
that's not going to go away.

00:16:04.710 --> 00:16:06.480
That's your movie, that's
you're AAA content.

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:09.010
That's your sit down, play
some time, spend a good

00:16:09.010 --> 00:16:11.150
weekend ignoring the kids,
shooting some people in the

00:16:11.150 --> 00:16:12.250
face, right?

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:12.630
That's there.

00:16:12.630 --> 00:16:13.865
TODD KERPELMAN: Good
wholesome fun.

00:16:13.865 --> 00:16:14.930
COLT MCANLIS: Yeah, good
wholesome family fun.

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:18.620
WOLFF DOBSON: I do that even
without a console.

00:16:18.620 --> 00:16:21.550
COLT MCANLIS: What I think we're
seeing right now is that

00:16:21.550 --> 00:16:24.960
we've never had an opportunity
for anything but that--

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:26.670
that's been the only medium.

00:16:26.670 --> 00:16:29.230
It's effectively like only ever
having bookstores for the

00:16:29.230 --> 00:16:31.940
first 20 centuries of human
existence, and then one day

00:16:31.940 --> 00:16:34.190
someone starts handing
out leaflets.

00:16:34.190 --> 00:16:36.040
And it's like oh wait, I can
actually get some data in a

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:38.650
very short condensed form, and
then go on back with my day.

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:43.160
And because we're a very
attention interrupted society

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:44.950
right now, these devices
we have in our

00:16:44.950 --> 00:16:46.210
pocket are very much--

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:48.350
I'm standing in line at the
DMV, I'm waiting to get

00:16:48.350 --> 00:16:49.470
punched in the face.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:51.920
Let me whip out and play some
games and then go back.

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:53.820
It's very much small
installments of

00:16:53.820 --> 00:16:54.770
little pieces of data.

00:16:54.770 --> 00:16:56.400
I think that's just a different
ecosystem and a

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:57.820
different model, a different
environment.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:17:00.080
And they both have their place,
especially when you

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:02.240
look at social games in
social networks and

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:03.570
who that caters to.

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:06.349
I thought Zynga's presentation
a couple years ago at GDC was

00:17:06.349 --> 00:17:09.460
completely eye-opening when
their lead designer had talked

00:17:09.460 --> 00:17:12.490
about her mental model
of designing games.

00:17:12.490 --> 00:17:13.304
WOLFF DOBSON: I remember that.

00:17:13.304 --> 00:17:16.690
COLT MCANLIS: Understanding that
when a house mother sits

00:17:16.690 --> 00:17:18.410
down to play a game, she's
just had a kid

00:17:18.410 --> 00:17:19.609
yelling at her for hours.

00:17:19.609 --> 00:17:22.960
She doesn't want to sit down and
try 15 times to shoot an

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:23.550
alien in the face.

00:17:23.550 --> 00:17:25.800
She want something that's
progressive and moving

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:28.160
forward, and something that
makes her feel like she's

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:29.830
getting investment
for her time.

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:30.800
That was really eye opening.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:33.230
That was a medium that, as game
developers, we'd never

00:17:33.230 --> 00:17:34.780
considered before.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:36.510
And I think we just have
more avenues to

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:37.410
explore these voices.

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:38.540
Now, I don't think anything
is going to be the

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:40.400
one dominant future.

